ned threat to their livelihoods. Between the Guerrillas and the State is an ethnographic analysis of the cocalero social movement that emerged from the uprising. María Clemencia Ramírez focuses on how the movement unfolded in the department (state) of Putumayo, which has long been subject to the de facto rule of guerrilla and paramilitary armies. The national government portrayed the area as uncivilized and disorderly and refused to see the coca growers as anything but criminals. Ramírez chronicles how the cocaleros demanded that the state recognize campesinos as citizens, provide basic services, and help them to transition from coca growing to legal and sustainable livelihoods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCocaxPolitical aspectszColombiazPutumayo (Dept.). 0aCocaine industryxPolitical aspectszColombiazPutumayo (Dept.). 0aDrug controlxPolitical aspectszColombia. 0aGuerrillaszColombiazPutumayo (Dept.). 0aParamilitary forceszColombiazPutumayo (Dept.). 0aState-sponsored terrorismzColombiazPutumayo (Dept.). 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aKlatt, Andy08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394204zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394204.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles